id not sort the input list.\n- It incorrectly calculated the differences between adjacent elements.\n\nThe corrected function will:\n- Sort the list.\n- Compare adjacent elements to find the smallest difference.\n- Track the two closest numbers and their frequency of the smallest difference.\n\n**Corrected Code Snippet**:\n```python\ndef find_two_closest_numbers_and_frequency(numbers):\n    if not numbers:\n        return []\n    \n    numbers.sort()\n    min_diff = float('inf')\n    closest_numbers = []\n    \n    for i in range(len(numbers) - 1):\n        current_diff = abs(numbers[i+1] - numbers[i])\n        if current_diff < min_diff:\n            min_diff = current_diff\n            closest_numbers = [numbers[i], numbers[i+1]]\n        elif current_diff == min_diff:\n            closest_numbers.append((numbers[i], numbers[i+1]))\n    \n    return closest_numbers, min_diff\n```\n\n**Explanation of the Corrected Solution**:\n1. The function first checks if the input list is empty and returns an empty list if so.\n2. The list is sorted to enable comparison of adjacent elements.\n3. The smallest difference is initialized to infinity.\n4. The function iterates through the sorted list, comparing each pair of adjacent elements.\n5. The smallest difference is tracked, and the two closest numbers are stored.\n6. If multiple pairs have the same smallest difference, all are counted.\n7. The function returns the two closest numbers and the frequency of the smallest difference.\n\n**Flaws in the Original Code**:\n- The original function did not handle empty lists, which could lead to errors or incorrect results.\n- It did not sort the list, so the comparison of adjacent elements was not done in the correct order.\n- It incorrectly calculated the differences between adjacent elements, possibly by using non-adjacent pairs or not considering all elements.\n\n**Conclusion**:\nThe corrected function ensures that the list is sorted, handles empty inputs, and correctly calculates 